title: Improved Track Drive Wheel for RC Tank

description.text:
This is a remix of part "track_drive_wheel_54_V1" for the RC Tank published by Staind.

The stock drive wheel has cavities with a rounded bottom shape for the pins of the tracks to go into. Under strain, for example when climbing up a steep hill, the rounded shape of the cavities forces the pins of the tracks away from the drive wheel instead of pushing the track forward as it is supposed to do. This leads to the track making a loud clicking noise when jumping back into the cavity after having been forced to the outside. Sometimes the tracks got stuck on my tank.
So I changed the shape of the cavities of the drive wheel. The pins of the tracks now get pushed along nicely and my tank runs with much less noise.
I have not tested this drive wheel with a fast setup. Right now I am using a very slow high torque setup with geared motors for crawling.

description.text:
Slight remix of the Robotic Hand v3.0 by Juan Gutierrez. So, for the most of the details see original project.

In this version I:

  • changed thumb position and shape so it represents human hand in relaxed position
  • added more material to the finger joints so that fingers are a bit closed in open position (if you look at a finger from a side it is no longer a straight line, but a curved line, like a bracket "(" )
  • added round corner for a string tunnel inside palm base, I thought it will make it easier for my printer to print (eventually this looks like a redundant measure, as it prints just fine without that)

For those who happen to live in Russia and have no Idea where to get those rubber bands, you can get those in orthodontic shops, they are 1/4” in diameter. In Russian they are called "эластики" or "ортодонтические резинки" or "резиновые тяги", they also have names for different hardnesses, I got "Медведь" 1/4, 4,5oz (strong), "Сова" 1/4, 2oz (weak one). Fishing line could be found in a supermarket or some fishing equipment shop.
ABS temp 225 . mesa 80 .

description.text:
Want a special NeoPixel ring, but cannot get right size or they do not have your favorite RGBWW chip? Create your own!
……………………
This customizable NeoPixel ring consists of holder, which is used as a jig to assemble individual NeoPixel breakout boards (like these https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01K4HCVDC) and also as a case to hold chips together and protect them from damage. Second part is a an optional cover, which can completely enclose ring in plastic and can be glued together with the holder.
Using this principle, you can create more complex custom shapes, but that's beyond this simple guide.
……………………
For soldering individual breakout boards together I recommend using thin tinned copper wire (not stranded) and thin soldering tip. It looks daunting at first but with all boards aligned and soldering with one piece of continuous wire goes really quickly and you can get it done under 10 minutes. Then use thin (midget) cutting pliers to cut wires between data (middle) pads on each board. Attached pictures should help to explain the whole process (good observer can see I also cut wire between + and - pads which is totally unnecessary, I just got carried away ...)
……………………
Ring is designed in OpenSCAD for extrusion width 0.5 mm and layer height 0.2 mm. I strongly recommend to regenerate STL files for different values because of very thin walls. 100% infill recommended, no supports required. Print with clear filament (tested with PETG).
……………………
Source file is included. If you remix, please also share your source file.

description.text:
This Lighthouse is based in the https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2687021 model (Thanks for Sharing!)
I cut the original model so it can be printed in different colors and used it as a Tinkercad exercise.

The total print time was around 18 hours, in my case by file:
Building Base: 10 hs.
Building Top: 2 hs.
Light: 0.5 hs.
Door: 0.5 hs.
Fence: 1 hs.
Roof: 2.25 hs.
Platform: 1 hs.

Color switch can be added to the Gcode file at the height you wish, in my model I used:
Building Base:
46.4
79.2
110.2
141.2
Building Top:
29.00

Note that this model color height does not honor original Light House. For reference please see: https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/2c/Brier_Island_Lighthouse_%281%29.jpg

Some parts have guides to enable a better reference positioning; some to be glued & some to fit by pressure.

Hollow structure allows for a lamp placement and hopefully a rotating mechanism with a mirror.

Next steps are to add windows and the metallic structure outside of the body. WIP so far.

I really enjoyed building this model.

As for the platform it can be removed:

The light can be glued but in my case i rather use two small bolts as I plan to change it for a new one holding a lamp and a rotating mirror. In either case the platform is marked for a correct placement:

The platform also has some guides for the fence placement that should be glued.

Added an observation platform and a door stop.

More comments to come once I add more parts to the model.

title: Drop Ceiling Curtain Holder System

description.text: This is a system to hang standard 1x2 lumber from a t-bar or drop ceiling in order to attach a vinyl curtain. The idea was to create a cold and hot aisle for our data center. title: E3D Titan Aero 40mm Part Cooling Fan Mount w/ CR-10 Mount

description.text:
Knocked this up because I wanted a way to mount a normal 40mm fan for part cooling to the E3D Titan Aero. As the titan aero wants to be mounted with a gap of either 2mm or 7mm between the extruder and stepper motor in order to keep the total thickness to 2mm I have modified evil_k's mount to make the wall thinner and gave a but more clearance for the large gear.

I have this printed and working. I have had to make quite a few changes to the mount and the stl is a bit worse for ware. If somebody wants to re-model it from scratch that's probably the way to go.

description.text:
Hello

This is the collection of remixed and aggregated items for a pro upgrade kit for the CR-10.

This should help you resolve and improve most issues with maintaining a clean setup for the CR-10.

See Pictures for final result of upgrade
Additionally, I've attached one full platter with all upgrades per section, or you can pick and choose the pieces you want. See the breakdown below of the hows and whys.

CamMount Parts:
Print one of each except for CamMount-ArmPart & CamMount-M3Wingnut
Print as many of CamMount-ArmPart as needed (this is the arm you can join together using M3 30mm screws and M3 Wingnuts)
Print as many of CCamMount-M3Wingnut as needed
You will need either Zip ties or 10mm lenght wood screws to attach base to plastic fillers on CR-10 rails.

Bed Mod Parts:
Print 4x Bed_Level Dials
Use Bed_Wire_Restrain_bracket and cover to manage bed cables

Bowden Parts:
Bowden-Cover + small 50mm piece of PFTE tubing for best effect
Bowden-Dial x 1 to visualize bowden motor movement.

Extruder Parts:
Print 1 of Extruder_support_Wires_ASide
Print 1 of Extruder_support_Wires_BSide
Use Zip ties and enclose both extruder wires and bowden tubing for secure cable management.
Extruder_Fang_OEM_Mod - Print one of these and use all the original parts of your CR-10 kit.
Add Fan Guard for protection of extruder cooler - you will need 2x or 4x 20mm M3 screws for this part.

Spool Holder Upgrade kit
Print this as a solid tangle free upgrade for stock CR-10 spool mount
Print 1 Nut, and 1 NutCut to attach spool holder to stock spool base.

description.text: A Von Koch Snowflake is a triangle based fractal. Starting with an regular triangle, the center of each side becomes the center for a triangle that is 1/3 of the side length. Then this is repeated for each of the sides of the resulting star, turning this into a snowflaky object. In this case, there are 4 repetitions of this proces.

title: Acrylic Edge Lit LED Sign
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: Laser cut sign uses an inexpensive LED lighting strip and includes a base. It's designed so the sign can be easily swapped. Requires 3mm hardboard or other material, and 3mm acrylic. The "lit" part is notched to fit the soft-rubber LED lighting strip, which better distributes the light through the acrylic. LED strip used is: http://www.dealextreme.com/p/flexible-24-led-light-strip-for-car-dc-12v-103267

• Replace Kwartzlab Makerspace logo with your own signage and export to laser cutter.

  • Separate parts to cut to the right material. Top is acrylic, bottom is hardboard or acrylic. Both are 3mm. If sizes other than 3mm are used then the width of the cutouts will have to be changed.
    • The "lit" part isn't cut all the way through so remember to use a lower power for those parts.

  • Insert the strip into the base and glue all base pieces together.

  • Insert the acrylic sign.

comments.text: Thank you for sharing. I have learned to use the automotive LED strips sold in automotive repair stores. They come in differing lengths and colors, and very easily connect to a 12 volt adapter.
comments.author: Richardj

comments.text: I'm not clear on what the power source is. It's not shown in any of your diagrams other than the fact that it splices into another cable. Are you just using a recycled brick of some kind with the barrel tip cut off?

comments.text: Exactly. All led strips have different requirements so I didn't go into details. This one had internal resistors so just needed a 12V DC supply.

title: Soporte de componentes para Printbots de BQ

description.text:
Presentamos unas piezas que te permitirán añadir sensores y actuadores a los Printbots diseñados por BQ. Los printbots más conocidos son el Evolution, el Renacuajo y el Beetle. Se trata de un soporte que tiene dos versiones: una versión horizontal y otra vertical. Ambas admiten hasta cuatro componentes. Adosando una tercera pieza al soporte vertical se pueden alcanzar ocho componentes electrónicos adicionales para el robot.

Así, por ejemplo, podemos añadir un par de intermitentes a nuestro robot, un botón para el encendido y apagado y un potenciómetro para regular los sensores de luz.

Los soportes están diseñados para las placas controladoras Arduino de BQ. Estas placas tienes cuatro orificios adicionales a los que incorporan las placas originales de Arduino. Los soportes se atornillas a dos de estos orificios especiales.

description.text:
My Rega Planar 3 Turntable's hinges broke clean off. I really love this turntable but without the hinges it makes the lid a real nuisance.

Be very careful removing the old hinge from the lid, they are fastened with some sort of rivet which will have to be removed. I used a drill, flat screwdriver, thin nose pliers and a little patience to remove the hinges from the lid. The lid seems to be manufactured from perspex which is normally very brittle and therefore care must be taken not to break it.

I used PLA for the print, the bendable part ends up being two layers thick @ 0.2mm layer height in the print. I am pretty sure the printed part will not last with PLA. Will be worth testing different filaments, please let me know your results with other materials like ABS, PETG etc. using the comments.

You will require four short 4mm bolts with nuts to secure the hinges to the lid. Currently it is fully functional and now also very easy to repair when needed :-)

Update 9 Jan 2018: Added a version which provides a support to screw M4 screw directly into the hinge to fasten and ensure nuts do not hinder 90% movement of the turntable lid.

This is a heat chamber extension for the Qidi Tech 1 printer.
I previously created a ventilation kit for the Qidi Tech 1, which greatly reduces the toxic fumes in my living room (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2434003).

However, since the normal heat chamber has quite a big hole in the back, some fumes and small particles still were emitted. So, I designed an extension for the stock heat chamber.
It consists of a upper frame in two parts, a lower frame and two supports to connect them (print the support twice). They can be put together with some screws. And you can screw some plastic sheets at the outside of the frame (see pics).

In the lower frame, magnets can be placed to keep the frame in place!

Hope you find it useful!

description.text:
Pebble Time Round Cobra Dock inspired by Behrendt`s cantilevered Dock design and some Apple smartwatch docks. Since receiving a Balco Touch 3d printer for Christmas I have designed several docking mounts for my Pebble Time Round SmartWatch. This snake-like version comprises 4 parts which hopefully interference fit together. I have included a series of blips on the tongue component which can be removed if the interference fit is too tight.
I have also allowed space for some ballast in the bottom of the product, I have used 2 x 16mm x 40mm x 3mm MS steel plates hacksawed from a 40mm x 3mm bar. The dock does not automatically need ballast but makes it that little heavier. An adhesive may be required to the base if bars or ballast are not used.
Parts of the print do require some support. I have included separate sets of components so they can be easily printed to individual colours.

After reading several articles about improving scan results with a Kinect for XBOX360, by using reading glasses (see below), I designed this lens holder for round glasses like these, strength +2.5:

https://nl.aliexpress.com/item/Retro-men-women-round-mirror-reading-glasses-for-Harry-Potter-metal-frame-glasses-plain-mirror-personalized/32689944322.html

You can attach The Monocle to your Kinect with tape or by drilling two holes (or adding them to the model) and using a simple rubber band, see the pics!

Further reading on this subject (thanks to frankvdh):

  • http://reconstructme.net/2012/03/26/reconstructme-with-glasses/
  • http://www.flickr.com/photos/tbuser/7013251877/
  • https://www.reddit.com/r/technology/comments/3xncm6/mit_team_uses_modified_kinect_to_boost_3d_scan/ (polarising filter, not glasses)
  • http://web.media.mit.edu/~achoo/polar3D/Kadambi_polar3D.pdf (large PDF on using polarising filter)

title: Wheeled APC Mk2 for Sci-fi Wargaming

description.text:
This is the second iteration of my previous Wheeled APC vehicle. Based on some feedback I'd received, I widened the wheel base a bit and added a twin barreled weapon to the front of the vehicle. It's still possible to add a second one of these weapons to cover one of the hatches.

This version also comes with two different turret options. There is a small turret with a fusion weapon option and a large turret with cannon, bolt and laser weapon options. I'll be making more weapons for the smaller version sometime in Jan or Feb of 2018.

The number of parts included looks SUPER intimidating when I view this thing, but it's totally not difficult to print and assemble. The core vehicle needs a body, both sides (w/exhaust on each) and 6 wheels. Everything slots together, but you'll want to use some glue. From there, print either the large hatch or the large hatch with the hole in it for a turret. The turret bits are all clearly labeled and are designed to go together easy. The extras are optional, but nice to have. At a minimum, I'd print at least one one the twin barreled weapon bits to slot into the front of the tank.

NO RAFTS NEEDED. NO SUPPORTS NEEDED. I've been particular in designing this to make it easy to print.

Follow me if you want to see more. I will definitely be making more... including a wheeled version of a larger tank used by the same soldiers!

I designed this using a variety of real world tanks and sci-fi props as inspiration. I worked exclusively in Google Sketchup, which is super easy to learn if you're only intending on working in non-organic shapes.

ABS filament diameter can change over time. Every once in a while you need to trust if two parts are going to mate propertly. So if you've just changed filament rolls make sure you know what your filament diameter in should be in RepG by printing this small object.
I actually made this to see if I could use it for my chess set, but it has been useful since then too.

Print this object then try mating the two parts together. (PROTIP, name the S3G file with the filament diameter for future reference.) If when you put the two parts together they're too tight no matter how you push they don't go then raise your filament by 0.04mm.
If they go together with a lot of effort but don't come apart raise your filament diameter by 0.02mm.
If they go together but then fall apart the lower your filament diameter by 0.02mm.
Then repeat the tests until they go together, hold, and come apart with ease. Then use that filament diameter for the rest of your tests.

description.text:
A 120mm collar with decorative socket screws. A kinky accessoire to your outfit at a party or if you want to play 'Fifty Shades' :)

The 2 parts lock together with a M3x35 socket head screw. The hinges are quite strong when printed in PLA, but are breakable in case of emergency. We have to keep it safe!

There are 2 versions, one with a solid ring attachment and one with seperate attachment.
It depends on the ring/lock you want to use…

The decorative socket screws are M5x8 and the holes should be tapped M5.
The 2 socket screws to attach the ring part are M5x16 and use a thin M5 nut on the inside of the collar. Beware that the screws are not too long and stick through the collar to avoid hurting yourself.

The top part holes at the hinges should be drilled 3.2mm to let a 3mm socket screw pass through. The bottom part should be drilled 2.5mm and tapped M3.

I used 3DanielW's fan cover and changed it up to something I wanted.

Origine

Inspiré des "Supports led DiscoEasy 200 Dagoma" de webgoum mais reconstruit d'une feuille blanche dans FreeCAD et adapté à des bandeaux de LED de 9 mm de largeur et 25 cm de haut.

Construction

Le support est construit en 3 parties :

  • la base qui se clip sur la tige verticale avant et reçoit le bas du bandeau de LED,
  • la partie haute à adapter selon la longueur du bandeau.
  • une pièce de jonction pour assembler les 2 précédentes.

title: 6mm Rod End Bearing/Rose Joint
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I had a couple of bad rod end bearings on my G2S, so wanted something to tide me over until replacements arrived.
These have a 6mm centre hole, and an M6 thread in the base, although all sizes are set exact with no tolerance, so you may need to file or tap some areas depending on the accuracy of your printer.
As regards extra parts, you'll need 2xM3 8mm screws, and I'd also recommend an M6 nut to use to lock the rod-end to the rod, as I don't know that threadlock would do the job here.

My copies were printed in PLA, and are a bit... creaky, but they do work, and I'd imagine lubrication or alternate material like nylon would cope fine.

Printer Brand:

CEL

Printer:

Robox

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm layers, 0.4mm nozzle

Infill:

30%

Notes:

You'll probably want to flip the top section over, so that the support interface is on the outside of the bearing.

File and tap until you get the fit you prefer.
Lubrication is optional, but recommended.

title: Speaker Enclosure/Hanger

description.text: This speaker enclosure was designed to hold an ip speaker that we'll be using in a school remodel we're doing. It had to be able to mount directly to a mud ring and allow that to be attached to the electrical box. The washers are to allow the nut on the speaker to remain flat without us having to print a bunch of support material. We edited the gcode on this when we were done to produce a single line of filament for each layer. We then printed it with a "MoarStruder" 1.2mm nozzle. It's pretty flexible, but it's help up well so far. The alternative was quite costly.

print_settings.Notes:: Print time with 200 micron layers was about 24 hours per mudflap. I tried to cut that time down by switching to 400 micron layers, but the material warped too much and didn't bond properly.

description.text:
Here's a link to a forum post with lots of information on the part and the process used to create it:
http://www.toyota-4runner.org/3rd-gen-t4rs/246409-finally-3d-printed-sr5-mudflaps-flare-end-caps-free-download.html

On that page these is also a link to download the full-size mudflaps.

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator 2X

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

200 micron

Infill:

30%

Notes:

I used ABS because that's what supposedly works best with the Replicator 2X

Print time with 200 micron layers was about 24 hours per mudflap. I tried to cut that time down by switching to 400 micron layers, but the material warped too much and didn't bond properly.

Required: coat part with epoxy

Sanded the mudflap with 220 grit sandpaper and then coated with epoxy (Smooth-On XTC 3D). It is very important you coat the part with this because the 3D printed part is not strong enough on its own.

After coating the entire part with two coats of epoxy, I'd recommend doing a little sanding with 200-300 grit (just the visible surfaces, the inside is bumpy but it's hidden when it's installed so don't waste your time on that), then hit them with primer and a few topcoats. Make sure you get a layer of UV resistant paint on there -- either the topcoat or add a clearcoat, or I'm sure any bed liner is thick enough to block rays.

Also, please be extremely careful with how much you tighten these! The material is decent for flexing and small impacts (after being coated with epoxy), but really bad in compression. I'd recommend using a socket driver (the type with the regular screwdriver-shaped handle) rather than a ratchet so you're less likely to overtighten it and cause anything to crack. Go very slowly and use loctite on the bolt threads so you can get it just barely tight enough so that it will stay in place. If you need more details on the hardware that is required for mounting see this thread:

http://www.toyota-4runner.org/3rd-gen-t4rs/246409-finally-3d-printed-sr5-mudflaps-flare-end-caps-free-download.html

Sanded parts ready for 2nd coat of epoxy (Smooth-On XTC 3D) Waiting for epoxy to cure before sanding and painting Single coat of epoxy, before sanding or painting Sanded part with epoxy, layers of grey and black grey primer. Ready for topcoat and clearcoat

description.text:
I really enjoy using my MPCNC, but I've always been a bit uncomfortable about wire harness management. In particular, getting power and control to the gantry in a "clean" manner that also did not require any attachment to the gantry itself for best precision was the major problem.

Taking a cue from another user, I designed a carrier for the drag chain that clamps to the side of the XY piece along with a track using 3/4" aluminum angle and two servo mounts. I used the very good drag chain attachments from https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1272581 to complete the routing of all the wires. I chose a clamp attachment method to avoid having to reprint and disassemble/reassemble the entire center piece of the CNC.

The center mount attaches with a clamp screw from either end of the side piece using a nut trap. The internal retention tab is beveled to avoid the axis bearings. The small piece spans to the larger mount part using a 6-32 screw, but it needs to be cut to length (approximately 1.7").

Servo mounts attach with 6-32 screws and nylox (or regular nuts) with a length of aluminum cut to size between them.

I ran Z-axis wires, spindle power (3 wires) and an extra wire for endstop across the mount. I used this drag chain, which is just about right for the number of wires: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01M0WRHUN/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&psc=1

The center mount also has a provision for a terminal block for spindle power connection, which seemed to work better than any connector option I'd considered.

title: 50/30 Monoprice Mini V2 fan (50mm Hotend, 30mm parts)

description.text:
This thing is a bit bulky but it works well. I wanted to use a 50mm fan for the hotend heatsink on my Monoprice Mini Select V2. The parts fan is only used for PLA so there is a little box on the side to mount a typical 1mmx0.5mm single pole slider switch. The little cylinder on the side of the 50mm fan mount is for a small capacitor (if your fan, like mine - does not like a PWM input, the capacitor is used to smooth it out to plain DC).

description.text:

title: Z brace using 1/2 inch wooden dowel

description.text: A small bracket I created. 2 can be used with 1/2 inch wooden dowel to create a brace of any length. I used this to brace the Z-axis on my Tevo Tarantula. After printing I put the 2 brackets on the dowel and adjusted the length to fit on my base and the vertical frame of the Z axis. I then squared up the Z-axis to the base and drilled holes through the bracket, the dowel, and out the other side of the bracket. I put a small, tight fitting nail through the hole to lock the dowel to the bracket at each end. The wood is very strong in tension and compression so makes a very rigid brace.

title: Tripod quick-release shoe for the Droid X

description.text:
A widget to mount your smartphone on a tripod, replacing the rubber bands you used before.
It is designed to fit the original Droid X with an extended battery.  (The battery actually extends out the back, requiring a new, larger backplate.  That is why it says ``X2'' on the back.)  If you want to use a Droid X or X2 with original battery, you can modify the Inventor file or the STL so that the gap between the fingers is about 1/32" tighter.
You can also use it without the tripod as a kickstand for your phone.

Just print!
I used 25% infill, 2 extra shells, 40mm/s feedrate, and 0.27mm layers.  The part is actually a little too large to account for the shrinkage of the ABS plastic (it fits perfectly in my tripod).  The overhang on the fingers is low enough (30 degrees) to be printed without any support.

remixed_from.author: mdiez
remixed_from.title: Creality CR-10S Z axis stop extender

title: Creality CR-10S Z axis stop extender - very small

description.text:
This is a remix of the part from mdiez -- on my CR-10S, the right hand side carriage was barely touching the right hand z-axis servo motor top mount. I shaved off a bunch of material so that there is only a little bit of increase in the bed height.

I think this needed when using Ikea mirror tiles on the bed (named LOTS -- 4 in a package) instead of the glass that comes with the printer. The mirrors from Ikea are not as tall. Might be useful for other situations too.

Original description:

This little yet cleverly designed piece, slips in the lower edge of the left vertical carriage to make it meet the end stop switch to bring a few millimeters extra of clearance.

This solves the problem some CR-10S and upgraded CR-10 have: when the Z axe slides the X beam downwards, the right carriage lower edge ends up resting against the second motor support just a tad before the left carriage lower edge triggers the Z end switch, thus slightly tilting the X beam, such that it loses its horizon in part of its Z axis trajectory. This tiny piece triggers the switch at an higher height, preventing the unwanted contact in the right side.

To install, slide the notch under the carriage plate, right above the switch. Notice the shape, trimmed to prevent the contact against the vertical post, and ensure the matching of this trimming. You may need to add some blue tape inside the notch to make it fit more tightly.

UPDATE

If you need this, your x axis bar (the bar that the extruder head runs on) is likely not aligned correctly. Odds are it is drooping on the right hand side.

You need to loosen the two screws holding the z-axis gantry to the x-axis bar (this is the gantry on the right hand side of the printer). Those screws are accessed from the rear of the gantry or the thing that goes up and down on the right hand side on the z-axis (it has the wheels on it).

So you loosen up those two wheels and then use something to adjust the height on the right hand side to match the left hand side. You might have to tweak it up a tiny bit. I suggest doing this when the printer is auto homed. You can use my leveling tool to do this. That is what I did. Once you have it right, tighten it down and check that the sides are equally high! If not, do it again. It may take 2-3 tries but once you've got it right on, it is smooth sailing from there on out! Problem solved! This was an extremely annoying problem to have but the fix is fairly simple.

description.text:
You ever look at the cubicle wall and wonder if you can add a shelf to those uprights between the wall panels?
If your cubicle is based on the holes being 1 inch apart, this should fit.
To measure the hole spacing, measure from the top of one hole to the top of the next hole. If that's 1 inch, this should hook in.
The bracket is about 6" deep and 6" tall.
The spacing from the front of the upright to the face of the cubicle for this bracket is set at 7/8". If your cube has a different measurement, you can try this, but I would recommend remixing it to whatever depth you need so the bracket is snug against the cubicle face.

PLEASE NOTE - I have not load tested these. They are sturdy, but keep in mind, they are after all, made from plastic. I would not put more than a few pounds per bracket. (Don't use for book shelves). These are good for displaying small things on lightweight shelves. If someone wants to load test these to see how much they can hold, I would be very interested to hear how they hold up.

Happy printing!

author: banbanmakes

description.text:
A 42mm ball gag with decorative socket screws. A kinky accessoire if you want to play ‘Fifty Shades’, or in any other way want to shut up your partner…
Believe me… the steel screws feel quite weird and you don’t talk much :)

The 2 parts lock together with a M5x25 socket head screw. 2 pins or M3x12 set screws lock the parts in place so they can’t turn.
The gag is designed to accomodate a 11x22 (3mm thick) steel chain. Of course you could use some pieces of rope also.

The decorative socket screws are M4x6 and the holes should be tapped M4.
The outer shell will print solid to get a much nicer print, but the holes can be punched afterwards and drilled 3.2mm
You don’t need to put all the socket screws in if you don’t want too… and PLEASE be carefull with the teeth. Maybe leave the middle row of screws out if it doesn’t feel ok. Play it safe… it’s only a game!

I printed one in Colorfabb nGen FLEX and that material is much softer on the teeth!
The parts are printable without support.

title: 14/20 Keck Clip - ST/NS Glassware Taper Joint Clip

description.text: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ground_glass_joint#Joint_clips

(ABS) Clip will weaken at temps of 90C and start yielding around 100C. Do not use for suspending large flasks or large assemblies if they'll be exposed to temps in that range. I recommend printing with about 75% infill and 4-5 layer surface. When printed solid, some of the connecting loops are prone to cracking at the apex and eventually splitting.

  • 24/40 Keck Clip: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:274563
    19/22 Keck Clip: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:275257

I recommend printing with about 75% infill and 4-5 layer surface. When printed solid, some of the connecting loops are prone to cracking at the apex and eventually splitting. I believe having less than solid infill allows the loops to distribute the flexing forces more evenly rather than concentrating at the crest. I haven't noticed any decrease in strength compared to the solid prints, and now that the loops are bigger, these clips actually hold joints together a bit tighter than my real Keck clips.

description.text:
After having many troubles with the original board, I decided to get an MKS Gen 1.4 & TMC2100s to fix the salmon skin issue. (New versions of Tevo Tornado printer board are using a different stepper controller and do not respond to smoother boards).

Also be careful which TMC2100s you get, most require smd level soldering skills to get steppers into spreadCycle instead of stealthCycle mode.

There are other cases currently available for the MKS Gen L, but they require days to print, this prints in only 30 minutes. The MKS Gen 1.4 is shorter and can fit in the original case. Alignment is a little finicky, but the board fits inside the original case without any issues. This works by placing board at an angle and retains the use of the USB port.

Does not require any additional hardware if you are willing to omit to screws from main case.

title: Prusa i3 Mk2 Ergonomic Control Knob

description.text: I wanted a better knob for the control panel on my Prusa i3 MK2, but none that I found on Thingiverse were quite what I wanted. I designed this version with two main advantages over others. First, it has a four-point star shape that comfortably accommodates your right thumb for navigation without looking away from the screen (with a recessed center area for clicking the current selection). And second, the back side has a flexible socket patterned after the original Prusa knob, which makes installation much easier than a simple hole on the back. In the sample shown, I changed filament near the end so that I'd have a contrasting ring in the center button area.

Printer:

Prusa Mk2

Rafts:

Notes:

Because this part is relatively small, I opted for much more infill than I normally use on larger items. The 35% infill provided plenty of support for the concentric rings at the top. A smaller infill percentage might work just fine, but I haven't tried it.
Due to the fine detail on the first layer, I found it helpful to print layer 1 at half the speed of the normal, already slower first layer. Also, a layer of glue stick on the build platform helped the details stick well. Once the second layer started, I cranked the speed back up to 100%, and the printing was easy after that.

title: SnowFlake Mobile - Desktop or Free Hanging

description.text:
This is a snowflake mobile created in BlocksCAD. This can be either a desktop mobile or a (simpler) free hanging mobile.

It uses the "earring" snowflakes from https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2728193 for the snowflakes.

The xml files used to create the geometry in BlocksCAD are also provided.

PRINT INSTRUCTIONS FOR DESKTOP MOBILE:

suggestion: white snowflakes
print 9 "earring" snowflakes from https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2728193

suggestion: black mobile pieces
print 3 small arms

print 1 large arm

print 1 base

print 1 lower arm

print 1 upper arm

print 1 connector straight

print 1 connector curved

ASSEMBLY INSTRUCTIONS FOR DESKTOP MOBILE:

I used heavy duty black thread to connect the snowflakes to the arms.

Attach 3 snowflakes to outer ends of the arms of the small arm using black thread. The distance between the top of the snowflake and the small arm should be about 1 to 5 cm. Repeat for the other two small arms. Varying the thread lengths provides a more esthetic display.

Attach the center of one of the small arms to one of the outer end of one of the arms on the large arm using black thread. This thread length should be about 2 cm. Repeat for the other two small arms

Attach the center of the large arm to the hole in the top of the large arm using black thread. The length should be about 2 cm.

Assemble the straight end of the lower arm to the base using the straight connector.

Assemble the upper arm (& snowflakes) to the lower arm using the curved connecter.

NOTE WELL:

The small arms and large arms will not hang level with random snowflakes with different weights. The thread length has an insignificant impact on whether the arms hang level.

ENGINEERING INSTRUCTORS: A student challenge would be to compute the equilibrium position of the small arm based on the weight of the individual snowflakes attached. It would be considered cruel and unusual punishment to ask students to compute the equilibrium position of the entire assembly.

OPERATION:

No batteries required.

The slightest breeze will set the mobile in motion when thread is used.

  • put it near a heating register and the air currents will set it in motion
  • when all else fails:
    --- gently spin the top of the center large arm
    --- or blow on it

PRINT INSTRUCTIONS FOR FREE HANGING MOBILE:

suggestion: white snowflakes
print 9 "earring" snowflakes from https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2728193

suggestion: black mobile pieces
print 3 small arms

print 1 large arm

ASSEMBLY INSTRUCTIONS FOR FREE HANGING MOBILE:

Attach 3 snowflakes to outer ends of the arms of the small arm using black thread. The distance between the top of the snowflake and the small arm should be about 1 to 5 cm. Repeat for the other two small arms. Varying the thread lengths provides a more esthetic display.

Attach the center of one of the small arms to one of the outer end of one of the arms on the large arm using black thread. This thread length should be about 2 cm. Repeat for the other two small arms

Attach a long piece of black thread to the center of the large arm.

Hang the assembly at a convenient location.

The stand is also used for the flying pig mobile: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2790832

print_settings.Notes:: Support everywhere, not just the bed. Lots of infill, the more the better.

description.text:
Started with https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2185533, then added my parts.

UPDATE 4: Some days I wonder why I try...
So the probe hole (lol...) was not the right diameter, WAAY off.. that is fixed and has been moved beside the radial fan.
Speaking of the radial fan, I somehow removed one of the screw holes for the mount, that is now back.
Also (attempted to give) better air flow for the hotend fan

UPDATE 3: Got it printing almost better then my MK2S.
Re-worked the model to look better and move a few small things.
Added a probe hole (heh...) for an 8mm inductive probe.
Moved the text and added more.
Moved things around for better movement of the air from the hotend.

~SOME TIME LATER~

UPDATE 2:So, I made another bonehead move. The radial fan mount was close to but not part of the extruder mount, needlessly causing instability of the whole thing. I also moved part of the radial fan mount to allow better pass trough cooling of the hotend.
Fixed in a new version (AnetA8_Flexion_Extruder_Mount-V3_repaired.stl)

UPDATE: Cooling... thats important. I'm not sure if you noticed but the fan doesn't really blow the warm air anywhere. It just hits the back and kinda whirls around just getting that hotend hotter and hotter until BLAMO! Something happens and stuffs broken.
So I have a new version (AnetA8_Flexion_Extruder_Mount-V2_FIXED.stl). A better version. A version that will rule over all versions before it. It will be so good... as long as I didn't miss something important again... This version just rotates the way the hotend sits 90 degrees. And lowered it because the first version (pfft that version was a little b***h) had the nozzle pretty much even with the backblate and the side carriages wouldn't be able to go low enough to get that nozzle down there.
TL:DR Rotated the hotend 90 degrees, lowered it by about 8mm (i think).

More pictures to come shortly.

comments.text: I printed it at 81% size (my build volume can't exceed 71mm in the Z direction), and I doubled the radius of the knob (so I could get a better grip on it, and give it more torque). It looks like if I'm going to keep using PLA, I certainly need more infill for it to be solid enough to work well.

3d Reprap Delta printer with a wooden frame, the frame can be produced on a CNC machine or laser cutter. Features include:

    • web site http://3dprinter.kiwi.nz/ Fixed and re-added the DXF files:

The wooden parts are designed to cut on a CNC using a 3.175mm bit.  
The two types of wood used are 5mm MDF (probably 4.75mm) and 9mm ply  
Paint both sides of the MDF in any colour you like before machining. My CNC has a max sheet size of 600x400mm so I cut the MDF in 2 parts)  
Assemble and glue the platform parts with PVA.  
The plastic parts are printed in ABS

title: Best President Ever! - Rick and Morty

description.text:
"Why would Rick and Morty want that?"

This scene makes me laugh every time.

I like the President and wanted to make a model of him wearing his "Best President Ever" shirt. For the shirt, I had to cheat and print it 2D and merge it into the 3D assembly.

I also wanted to try assembling an object on the printer and using the printer to bond the pieces together.

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Infill:

100

Notes:

No supports.

The Outline has to be printed last.

Mouth - Start with black, switch to white at 0.4 mm, switch to purple (or whatever you choose for the lip color) at 0.8 mm

Eyes - White.

Shirt - 2D print on paper the picture of the President wearing his shirt. It is scaled to match the model. Cut out the shirt and glue it to the recessed chest area of Body. Glue stick works fine. If any pieces of the shirt stick out, trim them flush to the edge of Body.

Outline - Black. Pause at 2.2 mm. Don't remove Outline from the printer. Assemble Body, Eyes and Mouth in the Outline, using super glue to tack down any parts that try to stick up above the top edge of the Outline part. They have to be flat. If any parts stick up too high, the nozzle will either gouge them or hang up. Not cool.

(Optional - at this point, burn some incense and offer up a prayer to the 3D printing deity of your choice.)

Resume printing. Monitor the final layer. The printer should print over the edges of the shirt, bonding it to the model. It will also print over the joints between parts, bonding them together.

It should all work out. Frankly, I'm surprised this worked at all.

Anyway, I thought it was an interesting way to add detail to a model as well as assemble the pieces.

Good luck!

LOL

The pixelation didn't print as distinctly as I wanted, so I used a pencil to darken a couple of the areas.

It's hard to keep the pieces flat. I had a few gouges, and had to draw in a few features with a sharpie.

Still working out the kinks in this technique, but I thought I'd go ahead and share.

title: 5/16 threaded rod Z-brace for Tevo Tarantula

description.text:
Quick frame brace for the Tevo Tarantula - in the style of the Prusa Mendel.

You will need to have already secured the Y carriage rails to your base board, you can use something like these :
  • thingirob brackets (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1457449)
  • my own brace (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2667150)

You will also need :

  • 2x 5/16 threaded rods - unlike other printers there is not enough clearance at the top, so 36.5cm is probably the maximum length you can use for these rods (use a rotary tool or a chop saw)
  • 4x 5/16 nyloc nuts - these are for the rod ends
  • 8x 5/16 nuts
  • 8x 5/16 washers
  • 4x M5 wood screws

Installation notes :

  • Build the bottom foot first, install all the nuts and washers, then tighten fully but take care not to crush and break it.
  • Install the nuts and washers for the top frame mount, but don't tighten them yet.
  • Attach the top frame mount to the aluminium frame using the M4 bolts and T-nuts
  • Tighten the nuts on the top frame mount, making sure that the bottom foot is flat on the base board
  • Position the bottom foot, it should push against the frame tightly, hold it in place and then screw it down with the timber screws.
Do not overtighten the nuts! This will crush and deform the mounts. These brackets are not load bearing, they just need to be stiff enough to prevent the Z gantry from oscillating as the hot end moves!

Tevo Tarantula

description.text:
This is a PowerPole adapter for the Elecraft KX3 Radio that (optionally) screws to the side of the radio to firmly attach your power cable to the radio and keep narrow gauge wire lengths as short as possible. It protects the power plug, prevents accidental shorting, and keeps the power cord from getting lost - all without interfering with access to any other radio function.

This adapter is designed to be compatible with:

  • the stock KX3 radio
  • radios with custom end panels; and in particular the Side KX end panels
  • the Side KX clear lexan lid
  • the stock KX3 heat sink

THIS ADAPTER WILL NOT WORK WITH ANY 3rd PARTY HEAT SINKS THAT I KNOW ABOUT, AND MAY NOT WORK WITH ANY OTHER 3rd PARTY UPGRADE.

To build the adapter you will need:

  1. Your 3D printed shell
  2. A stock power cord from Elecraft, DigiKey, etc.
  3. An Anderson PowerPole (15amp or 30amp)
  4. A #4 x 3/8" machine screw (sorry, Elecraft does not use metric parts)

Construction Steps:

  1. Cut the power cord to length using the cutting jig 3D printed part.
  2. Separate the 2 wire strands and strip ~5/16" (7mm) of insulation from the ends
  3. Crimp or solder the bare wire ends into the PowerPole center contacts. Crimping is the preferred method if you have access to the proper crimper...
  4. Insert the PowerPole center contacts into the plastic shells. MAKE CERTAIN THAT THE BLACK & WHITE WIRE GOES INTO THE RED SHELL AND THE SOLID BLACK WIRE GOES INTO THE BLACK SHELL. YOU WILL DESTROY YOUR RADIO IF YOU GET THIS STEP WRONG!
  5. Test continuity and polarity. If you don't understand what this means or how to do it; you should probably purchase a pre-assembled unit. (See below.)
  6. Carefully insert the cable and PowerPole assembly into the plastic shell. This is not easy. Tolerances are intentionally tight and you might break a few shells before you get the hang of it. I wedge the PowerPoles part-way into the shell and then insert the barrel plug. Once the barrel-plug is completely in place, I push (forcefully) the PowerPoles into position.

EDIT - 22 Jan, 2018 - In step 5 above, please note the orientation of the Red and Black PowerPole parts. THEY MUST GO IN THE SAME ORIENTATION AS THE PHOTOS! The red and black shells have slightly different dimensions. The fit is tight already, it will never seat well if you get it backwards.

A completely assembled and tested item can be purchased here: https://stores.ebay.com/n0wlradio

title: 25˚ camera mount for the VM2751 (intended for glueing)

description.text:
This mount is designed to mount a micro camera of the type VM2751 to a (relatively) flat surface, using adhesive silicone or another flexible glue.

A great glue for this purpose is Permatex Black Silicone Adhesive Sealant.
Silicone will stick very well to a rough surface like a flight controller.
The grooves at the bottom of the camera mount are designed to sink and grip into the glue.
If you want to make it stick to a smoother surface, its helps the bond when you roughen up that surface, or even drill holes into it, so the silicone has something to hold onto.

  • advantage: very strong and flexible bond, heat resistent
  • disadvantage: takes 12-24h to set

Also a very good glue to put this mount into place: hot glue.
The mounts are made from ABS, they will not melt at 200˚C.
Most hot glue will melt at that temperature, I suggest to use low temp hot glue.
What I like most is soft black keratin, which is sold in 11mm diameter sticks ar hair extension glue. Heat that stuff up to 180˚C with a SMD heat gun makes a great and quick glue for this mount.

  • advantage: quick to set (1-2 minutes), reuseable, removeable with heat
  • disadvantage: gets soft when electronics get hot, needs equipment

The http://enablingthefuture.org e-NABLE R&D group is looking for a means of locking down a control line when a finger is in position, so the position can be held without holding the control line, and thus the wrist or elbow, in position. For example, lock fingers around a bike handle, then bike without having to maintain tension on the wrist. This is a 'work in progress' exploring an approach. V2 Update:
  • Added groove in base to increase grip on line when locked down
  • Shortened bracket to ÃÂÃÂÃÂÃÂ½ length of lever
  • Can generate a row of latches in a single bracket
    • It's customizable, because shouldn't everything be customizable?

Parameters are:
  • Radius of large end of latch
  • Offset for pivot (the larger this is, the more extreme the difference between 'open' and 'closed' is)
  • Length of the lever arm
  • Radius of the pin (screw, filament, whatever)
  • Width of latch. Should be a bit wider than the line (and allow for angles, etc.).
  • Thickness of sides
  • Gap between base and latch (default is 0.4mm). Make this smaller to make the latch fit more tightly into the bracket, larger to he looser.
  • Tightness to make the latch closer or further from the base, in case we need to tweak this based on real world performance
  • Angle of latch for the preview, so you can see how it works
  • Line Radius. That is, the size of the line that you're locking down. This is used to generate a groove that the line is pressed into. The radius should be a little smaller than the line, so it's gripped when the latch is locked.
  • Number of Latches: Generate a row of latches in a single bracket.
  • Part to print: assembled preview, or latch and base to print.

title: FLSUN Base Kossel Delta Improved Hotend Mount for ABL

description.text:
The original mount on both mine and my father's FLsun Delta printers fit into its pivot very tightly and had to be forced and it would bind when trying to use the Z stop switch with the hot end for homing and calibration. One of us filed down the piece to allow it to pivot freely only to find that the hot end could now flop around as the hole for the M2.5 pivot bolt was over sized. This causes all kinds of other issues.

In addition to that, we noted that the M3 bolt that actuates the Z stop switch was not located optimally.

This part addresses both these issues.

1) The mount no longer pivots on the M2.5 bolt. Instead the bolt is simply a retainer and the part grips the fingers that originally caused the binding at the pivot. Instead, I have implemented a flexing action that cannot bind and increases the rigidity of the hot-end mount except in the exact direction that we want flex for improved precision when sensing the build plate.
2) I have relocated the M3 bolt that actuates the switch so that it is centered over the switch's button instead of further up the arm. This lowers hysteresis and further improves precision by requiring the minimum travel to trigger the switch.

Uses all the original hardware.

I am still gathering data, and intend to do comparative testing with the original part vs. my improved design. For now when running calibration G33 P10 on my printer, I am seeing Standard Deviation of 0.012 - 0.007 and lower regularly over repeated calibration runs, and my Z probe offset is currently at 0.3mm.

I also sent this to my father to try, and he reports instant improvements in print quality and calibration just feels and sounds more reliable.

Printer:

FLsun Delta Kossel Base

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.200

Infill:

33 - Grid / Triangle

Notes:

Printed with 4 perimeters

Printed in PLA, but just about any rigid plastic will work.

Setup

Just use enough spring tension to ensure that the moving end of the hot end mount is pressed fully against its stop surface, and then tighten the spring screw by 1/2 turn more.

Then adjust the M3 actuating screw to just barely depress the Z-stop switch so that it clicks.

Press up on the hotend tip repeatedly listening and ensuring the switch clicks both when pressing up and when you release the hot end again.

title: Hand Crank Mixer

description.text:
This is an old style hand mixer model I created to print out using my top down DLP printer. i plan to use the mixer to stir the resin in my vat (it holds approx. 13L)
The resin must be stirred occasionally to ensure proper distribution of the various components, otherwise print results may not be as desired.
I'd love to see what kind of results people get printing this on an FDM printer if they decide to try it, as I don't have one on which to try.
/edit I doubt it needs to be said, but just in case, you will need to print out 2 of the following parts to complete the model - Small Gear, Beater Shaft, Beater Cap, Beater End, and Top Handle End Cap. Other parts only need 1.

/edit I added a remix of some parts which might be easier to print using an FDM printer.
You can find the parts here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2751080
Marked as WIP for the moment, as I may add more or change if people have trouble.
If you try to print it and have any issues, let me know and I'll see if I can fix it up for you :)

For the past 20 years, I have primarily worked in 3d Studio Max, and I decided to try using Fusion 360 for this design.
Given this was the first time I'd ever used Fusion 360, I'm rather pleased with the results, though it did take quite a while, as I needed to learn everything as I went :)

I designed this with the intention of being able to print out all the components, and be able to assemble them in to a working unit without needing any extra fasteners.
If your print tolerances are a little loose, you may have problems with the shaft that sits inside the small gears falling out, but if you do, you're more than welcome to modify the design to add something to keep it in place. I'd love to see any remixes that get created :)

The gears were created using a couple of profile sketches, along with some formulas entered in to the user parameter section. Essentially, you enter the number of teeth you want on each gear, and the module value, and the size and rest of the parameters are calculated by the formulas.
If you need a gear of a specific size, it can be a bit tricky, but by playing with the numbers, it's possible to get at least close to your desired size.

I will be putting up a video overview of the process I used to create the model on my youtube channel and facebook page soon, which will also show the assembly animation, and model complete with joints and motion links in Fusion 360 to demonstrate it working.

Feel free to ask any questions, and I will do my best to answer :)

title: Marlin Ramps Firmware For Maker Select V2 / Wanhao Duplicator i3

description.text:
This is a zipped folder with marlin firmware for a Maker Select V2 (also known as Wanhao Duplicator i3) with a ramps gen 1.4 board.

Here is the kit I used:
https://www.biqu.equipment/products/mks-gen-v1-4-3d-printer-kit-with-mks-gen-v1-4-reprap-control-board-5pcs-tmc2100-driver-8825-a4988-12864-lcd

That kit is pretty easy to install. The LCD is a perfect fit replacement for the original. And the board will bolt on with this adapter:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1853712

If you use the firmware I have with the kit I linked your printer should pretty much boot up and be ready to use. Very minor wiring is needed. I would recommend getting some "dupont connector wires" which will make almost all of the wiring plug and play.

The original stock board on the Maker Select has two plugs for the Z axis motors. However there is only one plug available on the biqu ramps board. I used dupont connector wires to use the single biqu plug to connect both z axis motor connectors in series. It is also acceptable to wire them in parallel. If you are following these directions the E1 plug will be unused and you will have one spare unused TMC2100 driver.

I would recommend uploading the firmware with the LCD unplugged. My LCD had a common issue where the connectors were attached backwards. If yours has this issue it will just blink (and also prevent a successful firmware upload). It can be resolved by plugging the connector in backwards (tab facing the opposite way).

The TMC2100 drivers are amazing. They are massively quieter, smoother and efficient compared to the other options. I would highly recommend them. Before you install the TMC2100 drivers remove the three jumpers that sit underneath them on the biqu board. Lastly you will need a multimeter to set the vref. Look up on youtube how to do it, it's simple. I found I needed to set mine to 1.0v.

After everything is installed and the firmware is uploaded boot the printer up. Manually scroll each axis. Make sure when you increase the value for each axis it moves AWAY from the endstop switches. If it is going the wrong way you can either flip the connector or change the value in the firmware. This is most likely to happen on the extruder.

I hope this helps someone. I know when I wanted to upgrade my Maker Select it was pretty frustrating the amount of options and I wished someone had a simple easy to follow recipe.

NOTE - after getting everything installed I found there was no access to the SD card. I tried 2 different SD card extender cables and neither works. I just ended up cutting a hole in the side of the case with a dremel and sanding the edges smooth. However alternatively there is a full replacement case someone else designed:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2364807

title: Planetary Gear Fidget Spinner
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Another fidget spinner using gears, this time using planetary gears!

CORRECTION (JAN 6 2018):
The planet gears are fixed so that the hole diameter is 13mm instead of 11mm.

Things to Print

  • 1x EndCap_Top.stl
  • 1x OuterGearFrame.stl (or OuterGearFrame_countersunk.stl if using countersunk bolts)
  • 1x OuterGear.stl
  • 1x CenterGear.stl
  • 3x PlanetGear.stl
  • 1x GearFrame.stl
  • 1x EndCap_Bot.stl

Things to Purchase

  • 2x 626 bearing (ID = 6mm, OD = 19mm, T =6mm)
  • 3x 695 bearing (ID = 5mm, OD = 13mm, T =4mm)
  • 1x M3x25 Countersunk Bolt
  • 3x M3x10 Truss bolt
  • 3x M3x8 Pan Bolt (or M3x10 Countersunk bolt if making Countersunk version)
  • 7x M3 Nut

Follow the video instructions to build this spinner: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BEvVeLOcFUI.

Note:
The 3 planet gears used in this model is compatible with the gears used in the 9 gear fidget spinner. https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2502901

Tip:
The bearings spin better if degreased. The bearings used for this spinner was thoroughly degreased using ethanol, but other degreasing agents (e.g. IPA, acetone, etc) may also be used.
